ions: a strong electric arc enables nitrogen to react with oxygen in the atmosphere to form nitric oxide, and lightning provides natural high-energy conditions for the same outcome. This builds an explicit process bridge between environmental phenomena and reactive nitrogen chemistry. [Data: Entities (798, 797, 203, 202); Relationships (946, 949)]\\n\\nThese links also situate the chemistry content in real-world contexts (atmospheric events) rather than solely laboratory settings, showing how the community connects foundational bonding/reactivity concepts to observable natural processes. [Data: Entities (797, 798, 794); Relationships (946, 949, 944)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Lipids are framed by composition and physical-solubility behavior, with subtypes and biological roles implied\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Lipids are presented as a core biomolecule category within the “Chemical Basis of Life” unit, with explicit elemental composition links (C, H, O). The text also specifies a comparative point: lipids contain less oxygen than carbohydrates, which is presented as part of the descriptive chemistry of biomolecules. [Data: Entities (131, 200, 201, 202, 218); Relationships (104, 388, 389, 390)]\\n\\nThe network adds property-based distinctions: fats and oils are defined as lipid subtypes differentiated by physical state at room temperature (solid vs liquid). Lipids are also stated to be soluble in organic solvents but insoluble in polar solvents (including water), grounding how polarity/solvent type affects biomolecule behavior. [Data: Entities (356, 366, 391, 394, 133); Relationships (358, 359, 386, 387)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Noteworthy claims and learning activities appear, including ‘life originated in water’ and an assignment focused on water’s functions\",\n      \"explanation\": \"A direct relationship encodes the claim “life originated in water,” linking the water topic to an origin-of-life statement presented in the text. This